      "content": "Analyzing the layouts and text spacing in classic novels can reveal intriguing patterns. In Herman Melville's \"Moby Dick,\" for example, the deliberate use of arbitrary spacing and uneven indentation between paragraphs can be interpreted as a deliberate attempt to create a sense of tumultuous, hopeless underwater expeditions. The irregular line breaks and ample blank space also mirror the madness of Captain Ahab's pursuit. \n\nIn the case of Charles Dickens' \"Great Expectations,\" a closer examination of the text reveals a varying pattern of indentations and line width. For instance, penultimate paragraphs are often set flush left, whereas main titles and headed matter are indented. This layout suggests the mirrored progression of Vere Nemo and Pip from consequentially sorrowful yet stagnant lives, to one of ripping aberration.",
